title: Grateful Dead Live at Carrier Dome, Syracuse U on 1984-10-20
lineage: CD -> Adobe Audition v1.5 -> Samplitude Professional v10.22 -> FLAC
description:
Set 1

Bertha-> Greatest Story Ever Told, West L.A. Fadeaway, CC Rider, Ramble On Rose, My Brother Esau, Bird Song, Jack Straw

Set 2

Shakedown Street-> Samson & Delilah, He's Gone-> Smokestack Lightning-> Drums-> The Wheel-> The Other One-> Black Peter-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: Revolution

reviews.review_text: Thank You Charlie Miller! For yet another vague fuzzy memory brought back to perfect pure crystalline clarity!
Always a pleasure Charlie, I'd like to buy you your vice of choice!

First Show This was my first Dead show and I ingested some windowpane that was going around the parking lot...blew my mind. I was freaking, people were melting all around me, then the show starts we had great seats 20 rows from the stage...my friend grabs two of the folding chairs on the floor and starts running with them screaming towards the front of the stage. To this day I still think it was he who started the entire push to the front of the stage that caused Bobby to do the "take a step back" routine. I was freaking out the entire time, I just wanted to flee the building, but my other buddy kept me grounded, and the show was kicking. Still one of my favorite shows to listen to. One of my favorite memories in life, first year of college and truly a free time in my life...no worries.
Spacey Step Back Stay tuned at the end of CC Rider.  The Take a Step Back by Bobby is one of the spaciest occurrences I have heard to date.

"used to play for silver, now we play for life" the whole show was smokin'. Jer wasn't the only one rippin' it up. the entire band was intense,in time, and simultaneously pounding it out.
I've been to my fair share of shows, listened to thousands more and that's the cleanest, white hot, best jack straw EVER,EVER played. Jer's licks are indescribable,   
but the whole band played it and it leaves me speechless. All i can do is play it again, shake my head,play it again, and again and again......
What a terrible show A sloppy, uninspired dial it in kinda experience. Bobby is into something b/c he sounds f'ed up- esp. in set one. I'll pass.

Jerry killed it Was third row for this show ..The Band opened as I recall and THEY KILLED IT !!
Bobby had a bit too much to drink ..but JERRY KILLED it also ..amazing show and a great time ...I remember Jerry smiling in some trippy green light while rippin up a solo ....ahhhh ...good times ..

jack STRAW -johnyroastbeef I was 3rd  row too. The chairs didnt last long. Everyone was pushing forward so being that everyone was standing the seats just collapsed and were folded up all aover the floor.

While this is not the best all around Jack straws(see 79) the guitar break-jam before the final verse is what its all about and this one is ripping and goes on and on,bar  after bar which  is why it times out as one of the longest AND  best versions.

After Jack I couldnt take the crush anymore and went ALL the way back to the rear of the dome as far from the stage as possible

1983 and 84 Jerry's 'issues' with the persian  decended until the summer and especially fall of 84 when there was no hiding something bad was going on and not just the pers. His weight gain, long, greasy hair. To be frank his hygeine.The shows  of this period are 'dynamic' in that the highs are high but the lows are low. Shows were very uneven and Garcia rarely if EVER got thru a complete show tune g the lyrics correct on every tune. But as I said the highs were high and this JACK STRAW is one of those highs.

 I spoke to him years later about this period and he was basically going through opiod depression. Cared about little but staying high and 'numb.' As Jerry admitted its the ultimate comfort drug and William Burroughs commented that as long as you have your dope your 'happy' lying down and staring at your shoes all day

Ask me for a Contribution? The truth must be somewhere between 
the way over the top 5 star reviews
and Micah's 1 star beat down.

1) The Bertha>Greatest is hot out of the gate
West L.A., C.C. Rider -average
The first call to Take a Step Back is laced by Healy.
Ramble on Rose-nice version
Weir does some good backing vocals.
Bob has a North East Fall Tour sore throat.
Second call to Take a Step Back!
Way more in earnest this time.
Fire Marshal is Not a word you just toss around.
Esau-Again I just really dig this tune.
A good reflective tune perfect to diffuse herd mentality.
And if Esau don't get it how about a Bird Song
to help bring that mellow vibe.
Jack Straw-Perhaps the ultimate Set One closer!

2) Shakedown- Jerry needs a teleprompter but the jam is smooth enough SHAKEDOWN > SAMSON
Did this combo a few times/ loved the intensity of it.
He's Gone- lyrics at better pace for Jer.
He's Gone>Smokestack Lightning- this show becomes much more soulful mid-2nd set/  Jam is pretty sweet.
Decent Drumz>Space >Wheel>Other One.
>Black Peter- Classic, pretty laid back! (Brent has some cool organ work in laid.)
Lovelight!  a little bit more drawn out then usual
E) Revolution- Got one at Nassau and I thought it was a super cool tune. A great song for the encore slot.
Makes you actual stay with the band instead of one footing it out the door for Shakedown time.
Decent show a bit uneven at times. I guess i would rate it somewhere between 3 or 4 for this time period.

Everybody Step Back Sounds like a fun show if you weren't in the front.
Highlights:  Jack Straw

1984 Dead! This is another example of why 84' was a great year.Bertha /Greatest Story just rock out of the gate, Also a good Bird song & closing Jack Straw!? 2nd set is also very good. When I listen to this compared to any 92-95 show it's not even close. Find it ironic people think 83/84 where bad years. By 86-88 most of these songs were half as long meaning no to little jamming. I like 87' and 89/90 so don't get me wrong but for the 1980s decade the dead peaked in 83/84/85.

Jack Straw 1st off, once again, AS AlWAYS, a remarkable job. Kudos Charlie Miller. Stellar. As I'm contemplating what "source" to listen to of ANY show. If CMs name appears I'm done looking. 10/20/84 was a sublime show that ended a GREAT tour, my 2nd. full tout. Summer 84 was FUN, AWESOME, but in my humble opinion Fall was stronger. This night 10/20/84 is one of the reasons. Anyone who knows me, or read any of my takes knows how I feel about 10/12/84. One of THE BEST I saw outta aprox 400 Grateful Dead shows. Amazingly that this show was right up there too. I m listening to 10/18/84 "The Dancing In The Streets" as I write this review & it's screaming too. From 10/9/84 thru 10/20/84 the band was FIRE. 1ST off the energy in this monstrosity of a venue was always HUGE, INTENSE. I was there the year before, a baby still. & Listening to 82. . . . Something about upstate NY in general that appeals to this Midwestern Head (Detroit) & it culminates here at The Carrier Done. 10/20/84 was HIGH ENERGY' not to be contained from the opener Bertha straight thru to "Revolution" encore. Why did I name the review "Jack Straw." Self explanatory, no ? For sure THE STRONGEST "Jack Straw" in my memory. I will put it up against ANY "Jack Straws" from ANY era. It's THAT GOOD. Usually when I have the temerity to call some Dead song "The.Best" I add a clarification, "from my era, post 1970s". For example the "Morning Dew" they pulled out earlier on this tour 10/12/84 I to this day, without hesitation I  call it arguably THE BEST DEW OF the 1980s. Same with the "MINS" from 6/28/85 i feel it's the best post 1970's "Music Never Stopped." This "Jack Straw" I argue, if not the best, (admittedly a very subjective thing to rate . . .) "Jack Straw" that the boys EVER played it's certainly in the conversation. This whole show, again, is best described as ENERGETIC !!!!! Start to finish with the "Take A Step Back" even the "Black Peter" is crackling. The sublime "Shakedown>Samson" paring doesn't dissapoint. THANK YOU CHARLIE. If u ain't listened do urself a favor listen to all of 10/20/84 but FOR SURE cue up "The Jack Straw" it's a few times yearly that I GOTTA HEAR THAT ONE. I ain't the only I one HELLO my dear friend Patrick ! We DID have a time that night (besides the lame decision to split parking lot too quickly after show/after tour).

Fall '84 N11 Serious take a step back "jam" at end of Ramble On Rose. Bobby is not amused, warning that the fire marshal is gonna have to shut the place down if they don't just... take... a... step... back...   After an excellent Bird Song, penultimate song of set, we're treated to a ferocious Jack Straw, then set break, and... again: "We're gonna take a short break, we'll be right back. Everybody move back." Just move back, y'all!  

Shakedown->Samson to open the second set cooks!
